<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="morphological remarks">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Morphological remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Based on newly examined material, morphological characteristic of 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Jacobyana</taxonomicName>
is revised and updated with respect to the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Maulik, S" journalOrPublisher="Today &amp; Tomorrow's Printers &amp; Publishers, New Dehli" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" title="The fauna of the British India including Ceylon and Burma. Coleoptera. Chrysomelidae &amp; Halticinae" year="1926">Maulik 1926</bibRefCitation>
). Body roundish, strongly convex (Figs 2, 8, 14). Head with evident setiferous punctures (Figs 3, 9, 15); antenna short, generally not reaching pronotal base (Figs 2, 8, 14); third antennomere clearly thinner than first two antennomeres and about as long or longer than fourth and fifth together (as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana piceicollis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceicollis">Jacobyana piceicollis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana flurinae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flurinae">Jacobyana flurinae</taxonomicName>
); distal antennomeres (7 through11) distinctly longer than middle ones (3 through 6). Pronotum (Figs 4, 10, 16) clearly transverse (WP/LP&gt; 2.2), anteriorly narrower than posteriorly, without antebasal furrow; lateral margins distinctly bordered, with anterior setiferous pore rearward towards middle of pronotal side; posterior margin not bordered, clearly sinuous. Elytral punctation (Fig. 17) arranged in regular rows; interstriae flat. Hind femur strongly enlarged; all femora ventrally with a large and generally deep furrow as long as femoral length, with smooth surface, to receive tibiae in resting position; hind tibia dorsally clearly channeled with distinct apical spur; tarsal claw sub-appendiculate (Fig. 7). Ventral surface (Figs 5, 11, 18) with numerous setiferous punctures, generally rather uniformly distributed; procoxal cavities posteriorly open; metasternum about as long as first abdominal sternite; elytral epipleura wide and slightly concave.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Metafemoral spring (Fig. 19) similar to springs of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Psylliodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Psylliodes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Psylliodes</taxonomicName>
morpho-group (Furth &amp; Suzuki 1998) but likely constitutes a new morpho-group with dorsal lobe regularly curved, with rather long extended arm; basal edge straight, angled &lt;90° with central axis of dorsal lobe; dorsal edge of ventral lobe straight; basal angle of ventral lobe acute, short, apically pointed; recurve flange distinctly sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Oriental (India, Nepal, Vietnam and Sri Lanka) (
<bibRefCitation author="Medvedev, LN" journalOrPublisher="Russian Academy of Sciences. KMK Scientific Press Ltd., Moscow" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" title="Alticinae of Indochina" year="2009">Medvedev 2009</bibRefCitation>
) and Afrotropical (Democratic Republic of Congo, Malawi, and Republic of South Africa) Regions (Fig. 1).
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
Figure 1. Geographical distribution of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Jacobyana</taxonomicName>
Maulik.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="49" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana bezdeki" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bezdeki">Jacobyana bezdeki</taxonomicName>
sp.n. (LB = 2.64 mm), 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana centrafricana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="centrafricana">Jacobyana centrafricana</taxonomicName>
sp. n. (LB = 2.66 mm), and 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana sudafricana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudafricana">Jacobyana sudafricana</taxonomicName>
sp.n. (LB ♂ = 2.25 mm and ♀&gt; 2.43 mm) are the smallest species of the genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Sprecher-Uebersax, E" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="10" pageNumber="57" pagination="191 - 196" title="Zwei neue Alticinenarten der Gattung Jacobyana aus Indien (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae, Alticinae)." volume="75" year="2002">Sprecher-Uebersax 2002</bibRefCitation>
). All new Afrotropical species share a ratio of the length between antennomeres 3 and 4 (= 2) with 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
Medvedev from Sri Lanka (known only by a single female). However, all three African species are distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
by their smaller size (
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
: LB = 3.40 mm), interantennal space distinctly narrower than length of first antennomere (as broad as first antennomere in 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
) and, with the exception of some specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana sudafricana" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudafricana">Jacobyana sudafricana</taxonomicName>
sp. n., by the colour of the dorsal integuments, never uniformly black (entirely black in 
<taxonomicName authority="Maulik, 1926" authorityName="Maulik" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Jacobyana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jacobyana ovata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovata">Jacobyana ovata</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
